You&#39;ve found another bug where parts of the system are working at 
cross-purposes.

The AddRedirectFromRootServerToScope rule is only setting the &#39;isSeed&#39; 
flag, and returning &#39;true&#39; to have the ACCEPT decision applied, when the 
URI in question isn&#39;t already marked as a seed. But, the default 
behavior of LinksScoper already marked any redirect from a seed with 
&#39;isSeed&#39;. Thus the rule doesn&#39;t fire, and the redirect is never 
considered in-scope at all.

One quick fix might be to add a SeedAcceptDecideRule -- always crawl 
anything marked as a seed.

With that, you may not need the AddRedirectFromRootServerToScope rule at 
all. The behavior of LinksScoper + SeedAcceptDecideRule would be enough 
to get the URI scheduled. (It is later, when the scheduled URI is 
noticed as a &#39;discovered seed&#39;, that the scope is updated to accept all 
similar URIs.)

That said, the AddRedirectFromRootServerToScope shouldn&#39;t fail when 
LinksScoper has already done part of its job for it. Thanks for finding 
this, keep the reports coming!

- Gordon @ IA

